  <h2 id="overview">Diesel Fuel Centrifuge</h2>

  <p>Dolphin Centrifuge, based in Warren, Michigan, supplies purpose-built disc stack centrifuge systems for this application at 20 Gs with separation down to 0.5 microns. Rust sediment and sludge from storage tanks contaminate diesel fuel. Condensation causes water contamination. Diesel fuel centrifuges separate <strong>all solid particles and moisture</strong> from diesel fuel, ensuring clean fuel for trouble-free engine operation.
  </p>

  <p>
    Contaminant-free fuel is essential for reliable engine performance. Our diesel centrifuge modules keep diesel clean when installed between the storage tank and the day tank. They have proven efficiency and reliability worldwide for decades.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    Dolphin Centrifuge supplies a range of self-cleaning fuel purifiers for diesel, heavy fuel, and crude oils &mdash; available as complete modules with pre-heaters, starters, and PLC control panels.
  </blockquote>

  <h2 id="operation">How Does a Diesel Centrifuge Work?</h2>

  <p>
    Under extremely high centrifugal force inside the rotating bowl, water and sludge are spun outward toward the bowl periphery. Clean diesel moves inward and is continuously discharged through a <strong>light-phase outlet</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    The separated water is collected and discharged through a separate passage from the bowl periphery. The accumulated sludge is periodically ejected by the self-cleaning mechanism built into the bowl.
  </p>

  <h3>Can a centrifuge separate diesel from engine oil?</h3>

  <p>
    <strong>No.</strong> Disc centrifuges use centrifugal force to separate <em>immiscible</em> liquids (liquids that don't dissolve in each other). Engine oil and diesel are miscible &mdash; they dissolve in each other &mdash; so centrifugal force cannot separate them.
  </p>

